"Renger M., Wessolek G., Schwärzel K., Sauerbrey R., Siewert C.","Aspects of peat conservation and water management",2002,"Journal of Plant Nutrition and Soil Science","165","4",,"487","493",,,10.1002/1522-2624(200208)165:4<487::AID-JPLN487>3.0.CO;2-C,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0141515715&partnerID=40&md5=c06c458347e848b1b34f4166d002ea54","TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzufer 12, D-10587 Berlin, Germany; HU Berlin, Inst. of Crop Sciences, Dep. of Ecol. of Ressource Utiliz., Invalidenstr. 42, D-10115 Berlin, Germany","Renger, M., TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzufer 12, D-10587 Berlin, Germany; Wessolek, G., TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzufer 12, D-10587 Berlin, Germany; Schwärzel, K., TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzufer 12, D-10587 Berlin, Germany; Sauerbrey, R., HU Berlin, Inst. of Crop Sciences, Dep. of Ecol. of Ressource Utiliz., Invalidenstr. 42, D-10115 Berlin, Germany; Siewert, C., TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzufer 12, D-10587 Berlin, Germany","An extended water regime model was used for calculating the evapotranspiration, groundwater recharge, and peat mineralization (CO 2 and N release) for various fen locations with grassland utilization in dependence on the groundwater level. The results show that an increasing groundwater level leads to a strong decline of the actual evapotranspiration Et. For example, increasing the groundwater level from 30 to 120 cm diminishes the Et by up to 230 mm a-1. A positive groundwater recharge only takes place at groundwater levels of 90 cm and more. At smaller distances the capillary rise into the rooting zone during the summer months is greater than the water seepage during the winter months, so that a negative groundwater recharge-balance is reached in the course of a year. The CO2- and the N-release, as well as the annual decline in peat thickness, increase significantly with rising groundwater levels. The results show, that varying the groundwater level can influence the water regime and the peat mineralization significantly. The lower the groundwater level the less is the peat decomposition. The demand for a groundwater level as small as possible is, however, limited by an agricultural utilization of the fens. Choosing the optimum groundwater level should consider the aims (1) peat mineralization, (2) gas emission (CO2, CH4, N 2O), and (3) crop production. If a grassland utilization is supposed to be made possible and all three aims above are given equal importance, the groundwater level should be maintained at 30 cm. At this distance, about 90% of the optimum plant output can be reached. The peat mineralization can be reduced to 30 to 40% of the maximum peat mineralization. The gas emission amounts to 50-60% of the maximum value.","Carbon release; Global warming; Nitrogen release; Peat conservation; Peat soil",,,,,,,"Augustin, J., Mehrbach, W., Schmidt, W., Reiming, E., Effect of changing Temperature and Water Table on Trace Gas Emission from Minerotrophic (1996) Mires. Angew. Bot., 70, pp. 45-51; Augustin, J., Mehrbach, W., Steffens, L., Snelinski, B., Nitrous oxide fluxes of Disturbed Minerotrophic Peatland (1998) Agribiol. Res., 51, pp. 1-11; Christanis, K., Papadaki, A., Recont pead formation in northwestern Greece (1992) Proc. 9 th. Int. Peat Congress, pp. 69-77. , Uppasala; Eggelsmann, R., Peat consumption under influence of climate, soil conditionen and utilisation (1976) Proc. 5 th. Internat. Peat Congerss, 1, pp. 233-247. , Poznan, Polen; Eschner, D., Siewert, V., Sauerbrey, R., Einfluß von Torfart und Zersetzungsgrad auf Lachgas- und Methanemissionen (1998) Mitteilgn. Dtsch. Bodenkundl. Gesellsch., 88, pp. 415-419; Kratz, R., Pfadenhauer, J., (2001) Ökosystemmanagement für Niedermoore - Strategien und Verfahren Zur Renatuierung, , Ulmer Verlag., Stuttgart; Kretschmer, H., Zeitz, J., Pfeffer, H., (2001) Ökologische Entwicklungskonzept Oberes Rhinluch in Landschaftsökologische Moorkunde, , (eds.: M. Succow and H. Joost), E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart; Kuntze, H., (1984) Bewirtschaftung und Düngung Von Moorböden. Ber. Bodentechnol., , Institut, NLfB, Hannover, 80 p; Lehrkamp, H., (1987) Die Auswirkungen der Melioration Auf die Bodenentwicklung Im Randow-Welse-Bruch, , 995, Dien. A, Humboldt-Universität, Berlin; Mundel, G., Untersuchungen zur Torfmineralisation in Niedermooren (1976) Arch. Acker-Pflanzenbau Bodenkd., 10 (20), pp. 669-679. , Berlin; Sauerbrey, R., Schmidt, W., (1993) Bodenentwicklung Auf Entwässerten und Landwirtschaftlich Genutzten Niedermooren, Zeitschrift für Naturschutz und Landschaftspflege in Brandenburg, pp. 5-10. , Sonderheft Niedermoore, Potsdam; Sauerbrey, R., Zeitz, J., Moore. Handbuch der Bodenkunde 6 (1999) Erg. Lfg., 7 (99), pp. 1-24; Schwärzel, K., Renger, M., Wessolek, G., Sauerbrey, R., Soil physical characteristics of peat soils (2002) J. Plant Nutr. Soil Sci., 165, pp. 479-486; Succow, M., Joosten, H., (2001) Landschaftsökologische Moorkunde, , E Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart; Wessolek, G., Eschner, D., Facklam, M., Renger, M., Sauerbrey, R., Schwärzel, K., Siewert, V., Kennzeichnung der Bodenentwicklungsprozesse in Niedermooren (1999) Grundlagen Umweltschonender Bodennutzungsstrategien Im Norddeutschen Tiefland, (11), pp. 96-125. , ed: K. H. Richter, Ökologische Hefte der Landwirtschaftlichen-Gärtnerischen Fakultät, HU Berlin; Wessolek, G., Schwärzel, K., Renger, M., Sauerbrey, R., Siewer, C., Soil hydrology and CO2 release of peat soils (2002) J. Plant Nutr. Soil Sci., 165, pp. 494-500; Zeitz, J., Bodenphysikalische Eigenschaften von Substrat-Horizont-Gruppen in landwirtschaftlich genutzten Niedermooren (1992) Z. Kulturtechnik Landesentw., 33, pp. 301-307","Renger, M.; TU Berlin, Inst. of Ecology, Dep. of Soil Sci. and Soil Protect., Salzuf